The Cape Engaño lighthouse stands as a stark, skeletal sentinel at the easternmost edge of [Hispaniola](/Hispaniola), a testament to human endeavor against the relentless sea, standing firm within the dominion of the [Dominican Republic](/Dominican_Republic). Its coordinates, 18°34′01″N 68°19′35″W, mark a geographical point of significance, a place where land surrenders to the vast expanse of the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean). This isn't a place for sentiment; it's a place of calculated navigation, of warning and guidance.

### Lighthouse

The structure itself, bearing the designation Cape Engaño lighthouse, is a product of 1915 engineering, a metal skeletal tower built with a stark, functional beauty. Its square pyramidal form rises 20 meters (66 feet) into the sky, capped by a balcony that offers an unvarnished view of the surrounding seascape. It's an unpainted monument, its metallic skin weathered by salt and sun, bearing the marks of its long service. The light, first ignited in 1990, emanates from a focal height of 43 meters (141 feet), casting its beam a distance of 11 nautical miles (20 kilometers; 13 miles). Its characteristic, Fl W 5s, is a silent, rhythmic pulse—a single white flash every five seconds—a code understood by mariners navigating these often treacherous waters.

### Location

Cabo Engaño is more than just a point on a map; it's the easternmost extremity of [Hispaniola](/Hispaniola), a dramatic geographical feature firmly within the [Dominican Republic](/Dominican_Republic). The cape itself is known for its submerged dangers, treacherous reefs that lie in proximity to the historic capital of [Santo Domingo](/Santo_Domingo). It's a stark reminder that even in paradise, peril lurks beneath the surface. The modern world's proximity is marked by the [Punta Cana International Airport](/Punta_Cana_International_Airport), the nation's busiest air hub, situated a stone's throw south of the cape, a juxtaposition of ancient geography and contemporary transit.

The waters off Cape Engaño have witnessed maritime drama. In 1502, a significant Spanish fleet, numbering between 30 and 32 vessels laden with treasure and colonists, met its fate during a violent storm. This ill-fated expedition, dispatched under the authority of Governor Nicolas Ovando, was bound for Spain. While a handful of ships, battered but afloat, managed to limp back to their port of origin, only one, the "Aguja," successfully completed the perilous journey to Spain. This historical footnote underscores the enduring challenges of navigating these seas, a narrative etched into the very fabric of the cape.

### Climate

The climate data for Cape Engaño, often associated with the nearby locale of [Punta Cana](/Punta_Cana), paints a picture of tropical warmth, a consistent embrace of heat and humidity. From 1961 to 1990, the temperature records reveal a predictable pattern. Record highs often breach the 30°C (87.8°F) mark, with the hottest temperatures typically occurring in the summer months, peaking in July at 34.7°C (94.5°F). Daily mean temperatures hover around a comfortable 26.2°C (79.2°F) year-round, rarely dipping below the low 20s Celsius (high 70s Fahrenheit) even at night.

Rainfall, while present, is not a constant deluge. The annual average hovers around 1,102.6 mm (43.41 inches), with the heaviest precipitation typically falling in October, when the region can expect approximately 152.1 mm (5.99 inches). Conversely, February and March tend to be drier. The average number of rainy days, defined as those with at least 0.1 mm of precipitation, is around 10-11 days per month, indicating that even on rainy days, the sun often finds a way through.

[Relative humidity](/Relative_humidity) is consistently high, averaging around 82.4% annually, a characteristic of tropical maritime climates. This humidity contributes to the palpable warmth and often contributes to the picturesque, if sometimes muggy, atmosphere. [Sunshine hours](/Sunshine_duration) are abundant, with an average of over 3,000 hours per year, suggesting that despite the occasional rain, the region is bathed in sunlight for a significant portion of the year. The data, meticulously collected and presented by the [World Meteorological Organization](/World_Meteorological_Organization) and [NOAA](/NOAA), provides a clear, if somewhat sterile, portrait of the environmental conditions at Cape Engaño. It’s a climate that shapes the landscape, influences maritime activity, and dictates the rhythm of life in this corner of the [Dominican Republic](/Dominican_Republic).

